00:00:00.771 --> 00:00:02.299
Voiceover:Alma has developed a new kind

00:00:02.299 --> 00:00:03.331
of antibiotic.

00:00:03.331 --> 00:00:05.960
For the antibiotic to be
sufficiently effective,

00:00:05.960 --> 00:00:08.458
it has to kill at least 90% of bacteria

00:00:08.458 --> 00:00:10.651
when applied to a
harmful bacteria culture.

00:00:11.097 --> 00:00:13.139
She applied her antibiotic to a petri dish

00:00:13.139 --> 00:00:14.715
full of harmful bacteria,

00:00:14.715 --> 00:00:16.442
waited for it to take effect,

00:00:16.442 --> 00:00:18.443
and then tried to estimate the percentage

00:00:18.443 --> 00:00:19.954
of dead bacteria in it.

00:00:20.354 --> 00:00:23.498
She took a random sample of 300 bacteria

00:00:23.498 --> 00:00:26.557
and found that 94% of them were dead.

00:00:26.557 --> 00:00:28.974
Then she calculated the margin of error

00:00:28.974 --> 00:00:30.467
and found that the true percentage of

00:00:30.467 --> 00:00:33.689
dead bacteria is most
likely to be above 90%.

00:00:33.965 --> 00:00:35.166
So, what's happening over here,

00:00:35.166 --> 00:00:36.560
she's trying to figure out what percentage

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:40.287
of the total population of bacteria died.

00:00:40.287 --> 00:00:41.991
Maybe there's something
about this bacteria,

00:00:41.991 --> 00:00:44.288
maybe when you look at it from, you know,

00:00:44.288 --> 00:00:45.115
the naked eye,

00:00:45.115 --> 00:00:46.603
you can't tell whether the bacteria

00:00:46.603 --> 00:00:47.937
died or not.

00:00:47.937 --> 00:00:50.878
So, she decides to estimate
the true percentage

00:00:50.878 --> 00:00:55.705
by sampling 300 individual bacterium,

00:00:55.705 --> 00:00:58.271
or by sampling ... I always forget the

00:00:58.271 --> 00:00:59.019
singular case.

00:00:59.019 --> 00:01:01.304
By sampling 300 bacteria,

00:01:01.304 --> 00:01:04.163
and then in her sample she found that 94%

00:01:04.163 --> 00:01:05.398
of them were dead.

00:01:05.398 --> 00:01:07.851
Then the margin of error tells us,

00:01:07.851 --> 00:01:10.601
because the margin of
error says it's unlikely,

00:01:10.601 --> 00:01:13.226
or that it's very likely that the true

00:01:13.226 --> 00:01:14.633
percentage is above 90%.

00:01:14.633 --> 00:01:16.573
That means that given that you sample

00:01:16.573 --> 00:01:17.866
300 bacteria,

00:01:17.866 --> 00:01:20.545
it's very unlikely that
the true percentage

00:01:20.545 --> 00:01:22.016
is below 90%.

00:01:22.016 --> 00:01:24.147
So, she could feel reasonably confident

00:01:24.147 --> 00:01:25.961
that in her petri dish,

00:01:25.961 --> 00:01:28.481
more than 90% of the population

00:01:28.481 --> 00:01:31.139
did indeed die.

00:01:31.846 --> 00:01:33.159
Now, let's answer these questions.

00:01:33.159 --> 00:01:37.308
What type of statistical
study did Alma use?

00:01:37.769 --> 00:01:39.515
Well, she used a ...

00:01:39.515 --> 00:01:42.138
she's trying to estimate a parameter

00:01:42.138 --> 00:01:43.271
for population, in this case,

00:01:43.271 --> 00:01:44.828
the parameter was the percentage of

00:01:44.828 --> 00:01:46.954
all of the bacteria that died.

00:01:46.954 --> 00:01:49.291
She couldn't observe that directly,

00:01:49.291 --> 00:01:51.529
so instead, she took a random sample

00:01:51.529 --> 00:01:53.437
of the bacteria in the petri dish,

00:01:53.437 --> 00:01:54.809
and she used ...

00:01:54.809 --> 00:01:57.204
she calculated the static for them,

00:01:57.204 --> 00:01:58.737
94% of them were dead,

00:01:58.737 --> 00:02:00.225
and that's her estimate for the

00:02:00.225 --> 00:02:01.661
population parameter.

00:02:01.661 --> 00:02:03.553
The percentage of the
population that died.

00:02:03.553 --> 00:02:05.160
So this is ... when you're using a ...

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:07.686
when you're using a random sample

00:02:07.686 --> 00:02:09.693
to generate a statistic,

00:02:09.693 --> 00:02:12.022
which estimates a
parameter for a population,

00:02:12.022 --> 00:02:13.641
that's a sample study.

00:02:13.641 --> 00:02:16.398
So, she ran a sample study.

00:02:16.798 --> 00:02:18.195
